---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="About — authored.systems" description="The thinking behind authored.systems and the team building it.">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <header class="mb-12">
      <p class="font-mono text-sm text-accent mb-4 tracking-wide">ABOUT</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight">
        Structure first. AI second.
      </h1>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p>
        authored.systems is a framework for building operational systems where humans author the rules and machines enforce them.
      </p>

      <p>
        It emerged from building real software for real operations — property management, fitness facilities,
        field services — and discovering that the same six structures kept appearing regardless of industry.
        We didn't design them. We discovered them.
      </p>

      <p>
        The framework is simple: every operation decomposes into six primitives — Policy, Procedure, Asset, Person, Event, Ledger.
        AI belongs at the edges (perception, optimization, pattern detection), not at the center (orchestration, decision-making).
        The brain is deterministic. The senses are AI. The record is immutable.
      </p>

      <h2>The Product</h2>

      <p>
        These principles power <a href="https://onrunbook.com">Runbook</a> — an operational platform built on the six primitives.
        Runbook turns implicit operations into explicit, inspectable, improvable systems.
      </p>

      <h2>The Author</h2>

      <p>
        authored.systems is written by Jeff Sabir. Jeff runs a property management company and builds the software to run it.
        The framework came from trying to build a checklist app and discovering that every "simple" feature required the same six concepts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
